<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-10-13T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-10-13T06:00:00-05:00" n="531" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d531">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">693.24/1662: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-10-13T18:00:00+07:00">October 13,
                                1943—6 p.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received October 13—12:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1936. Consul [at] Tihwa reported that Provincial Chairman informed him
                        October 9 that Soviets base objection to transshipment of war material to
                        China on desire to avoid arousing Japanese suspicion, that Soviet Ambassador
                        [at] Chungking said he would prefer to have to refer to Moscow Chinese
                        proposal that some military goods be transported, and that the “plan can not
                        be effected at present”.</p>
                    <p>Foregoing refers to Department’s 1407, October 1.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>